Basic Idea

Provide some useful visualizations of common risk information measures as interactive tools (in R and Shiny) for fostering transparent risk communication and teaching purposes.

Mathematical Background

Bayesian inference

H.lbl <- "H" # Hypothesis
E.lbl <- "E" # Evidence (E) or Decision (D)

Bayesâ rule describes the probability \(p\) of a hypothesis \(H\) given some evidence \(E\) as:

\[ p(H|E) = \frac{p(E|H) \times\ p(H)} {p(E)} \]

By further decomposing the denominator \(p(E)\) into two mutually exclusive parts \(p(E|H) \times\ p(H) + p(E|\neg H) \times\ p(\neg H)\) we get:

\[ p(H|E) = \frac{p(E|H) \times\ p(H)} {p(E|H) \times\ p(H) + p(E|\neg H) \times\ p(\neg H)} \]

Probabilities vs.Â natural frequencies

Information (e.g., clinical variables) is often expressed as probabilities (e.g., prev) or even as conditional probabilities (sens/spec, ppv/npv).

Many quantities can be expressed either as probabilities or as natural frequencies. Although both representations are mathematically equivalent, a basic claim (e.g., by Gigerenzer et al.) is that people struggle when information is expressed in terms of probabilities, but not when the same information is expressed in terms of natural frequencies.

The notion of âBayesian inferenceâ looks and sounds complicated, but â at its core â we typically aim to understand the interplay between a small set of variables for a specific scenario.

Scenario

Scenario

Any example problem starts with the definition of a concrete scenario:

  1. A specific population of size N;
  2. A condition that is being considered (with 2 states TRUE vs. FALSE);
  3. A decision (clinical judgment) that classifies the condition (into positive or negative, or a judgment of TRUE vs. FALSE);
  4. Some parameters (typically probabilities) that are provided (see below);
  5. Some parameters (typically probabilities) that are asked (see below).

Environment parameters

Any specific scenario contains several numeric parameters that are either inputs or outputs.

Inputs

  1. Prevalence: prev

  2. Sensitivity: sens = \(p\)(decision positive | condition true)

  3. Specificity: spec = \(p\)(decision negative | condition false)

or

  1. False alarm rate:
    fart

Outputs

  1. Positive predictive value ppv

  2. Negative predictive value npv

Notes

  • All these parameters are probabilities (on a scale from 0 to 1 or as percentages from 0% to 100%).
  • Parameters 2. to 5. are defined as conditional probabilities.

Number of cases

Note that we immediately translate probabilities into natural frequencies:

Truth conditions

  1. Actual number of true cases:

n.true = N \(\times\) prev

  1. Actual number of false cases:

n.false = 1 â n.true
= N \(\times\) (1 â prev)

Decisions

  1. Number of positive decisions:

n.pos = â¦

  1. Number of negative decisions:

n.neg = â¦

Combinations (SDT)

  1. Number of hits (aka. true positives):

n.hi = n.true \(\times\) sens
= N \(\times\) prev \(\times\) sens
= n.true - n.mi

  1. Number of misses (aka. false negatives or omissions) n.mi:

n.mi = n.true \(\times\) (1 â sens)
= (N \(\times\) prev) \(\times\) (1 â sens)
= n.true â n.hi

  1. Number of false alarms (aka. false positives):

n.fa = n.false \(\times\) fart
= N \(\times\) (1 â prev) \(\times\) fart
= N \(\times\) (1 â prev) \(\times\) (1 â spec)
= n.false â n.cr

  1. Number of correct rejections (aka. true negatives):

n.cr = n.false \(\times\) spec
= N \(\times\) (1 â prev) \(\times\) spec
= n.false â n.fa

Predictive values

Positive predictive value (\(PPV\))

Definition: In statistics and diagnostic tests, the positive predictive value (\(PPV\)) is the proportion of positive decisions that are true positives (hits).

In terms of natural frequencies, the \(PPV\) is defined (quite simply) as:

\[ \begin{aligned} PPV &= \frac{\textrm{true positives}}{\textrm{positive decisions}}\\ &= \frac{\textrm{true positives}}{\textrm{true positives} + \textrm{false positives}}\\ &= \frac{\textrm{hits}}{\textrm{hits} + \textrm{false alarms}} \end{aligned} \]

However, given that

  • n.hi = N \(\times\) prev \(\times\) sens
  • n.fa = N \(\times\) (1 â prev) \(\times\) (1 â spec)

we can express this (considerably more obscurely) as a fraction of probabilities:

\[ \begin{aligned} PPV &= \frac{(N \times\ prev) \times\ sens} {(N \times\ prev) \times\ sens + [N \times\ (1 - prev)] \times\ (1 - spec)}\\ &= \frac{prev \times\ sens} {prev \times\ sens + (1 - prev) \times\ (1 - spec)} \end{aligned} \]

  1. \(PPV\) is the reversed conditional probability of sens:
  • \(PPV\) = \(p\)(condition true | decision positive)
  • sens = \(p\)(decision positive | condition true)
  1. The complement of \(PPV\) is the false discovery rate (\(FDR\)):

\[ FDR = 1 - PPV \]

Negative predictive value (\(NPV\))

Definition: In statistics and diagnostic tests, the negative predictive value (\(NPV\)) is the proportion of negative decisions that are true negatives (correct rejections).

  1. In terms of natural frequencies, the \(NPV\) is defined (quite simply) as:

\[ \begin{aligned} NPV &= \frac{true\ negatives}{negative\ decisions}\\ &= \frac{true\ negatives}{true\ negatives + false\ negatives}\\ &= \frac{correct\ rejections}{correct\ rejections\ + misses} \end{aligned} \]

  1. However, given that
  • n.cr = N \(\times\) (1 â prev) \(\times\) spec
  • n.mi = N \(\times\) prev \(\times\) (1 â sens)

we can express this (considerably more obscurely) as a fraction of probabilities:

\[ \begin{aligned} NPV &= \frac{N \times\ (1 - prev) \times\ spec} {(N \times\ (1 - prev) \times\ spec) + [N \times\ prev \times\ (1 - sens)]} \\ &= \frac{(1 - prev) \times\ spec} {(1 - prev) \times\ spec + prev \times\ (1 - sens)} \end{aligned} \]

  1. \(NPV\) is the reversed conditional probability of spec:
  • \(NPV\) = \(p\)(condition false | decision negative)
  • spec = \(p\)(decision negative | condition false)
  1. The complement of the \(NPV\) is the false omission rate (\(FOR\)):

\[ FOR = 1 - NPV \]

Functionality

Our approach: From theories to tools (rather than the reverse, Gigerenzer, 1991a).

Levels and perspectives

3 different levels with alternative perspectives:

  1. Viewing population as collection of individuals or cases: table vs.Â icon array

  2. Aggregation and categorization (SDT): confusion table, mosaic plot, tree of natural frequencies

  3. Resulting posteriors: PV curves and planes

Interactions: Sorting, sliding, and sampling:

  1. Sorting is the opposite of shuffling (randomization):

  2. Sliders and observing corresponding interactive and dynamic shifts of outputs as a function of own actions encourages viewing inputs as continuous variables (Gigerenzer et al., 1988) and thus may help to make cognitive illusions disappear (Gigerenzer, 1991b).

  3. Sampling encourages differentiation of population vs. sample and a perspective by description and one by experience. Allows developing and testing intuitions about sample size (Sedlmeier & Gigerenzer, 1997).

Initial Set of Tools

Based on a set of common parameters: population size N, prevalence prev, sensitivity sens, specificity spec (or false alarm rate fa = 1 - spec).

  1. Diagnostic measures based on natural frequencies:
    1. as 2x2 confusion table (of hits, false alarms, misses, correct rejections)
    2. as tree with natural frequencies

  2. Icon array

  3. Graphical illustrations of PPV and NPV (given N, prevalence, sensitivity, specificity):
    1. 2D version: PPV and NPV as function of prevalence (on \(x\)-axis), with \(sens\) and \(spec\) as parameters to set.
    2. 3D version: PPV/NPV as function of \(sens\) on \(x\)-axis, \(spec\) on \(z\)-axis, with \(prevalence\) as parameter to set.

Allow setting and playing with basic parameters or reading in examples from the literature.

Future extensions

  1. Allow for randomization and sampling

  2. Extend to decisions on non-dichotomous distributions (SDT).

  3. Extend to the topics of scientific reasoning: Cell A bias and biased evidence detection.

  4. Include info on screening biases (lead time vs.Â over-diagnosis bias).

Basics

Main Parameters

The following variables should be used (and updated) by all parts:

## Inputs used in all representations:
# (a) as parameters:
N <- 100 # N in population
prev <- .15 # prevalence in population = p(true positive)
sens <- .85 # sensitivity = p(positive decision | true positive)
spec <- .75 # specificity = p(negative decision | true negative)

# (b) as environment list:
e1 <- list("name" = "Demo",  # name (e.g., HIV, mammography, ...)
           "N" = 100,        # N in population
           "prev" = .15,     # prevalence in population = p(true positive)
           "sens" = .85,     # sensitivity = p(positive decision | true positive)
           "spec" = .75,     # specificity = p(negative decision | true negative)
           "source" = "Source info" # information source (e.g., citation)
           )

Alternatively, we could define or read in a set of existing examples:

## 1. HIV (a) [Source: Gigerenzer (2013), p. 53]:
name <- "HIVa"
N <- 100000     # women
prev <- 1/10000 # p(HIV)
sens <- 1.0     # p(pos | HIV ) 
spec <- (1 - 5/100000) # 1 - p(fa) = 1 - (pos | no HIV)
source <- "Gigerenzer (2013), p. 53"

## 2. HIV (b) [Source: Gigerenzer (2013), p. 53]:
name <- "HIVb"
N <- 250000     # women
prev <- 1/10000 # p(HIV)
sens <- 1.0     # p(pos | HIV ) 
spec <- (1 - 1/250000) # 1 - p(fa) = 1 - (pos | no HIV)
source <- "Gigerenzer (2013), p. 53"

## 3. Breast cancer  [Source: Gigerenzer (2013), p. 213--221]:
name <- "Breast cancer"
N <- 1000         # women (50yrs, no symptoms, routine mammography screening)
prev <- 10/1000   # p(breast cancer)
sens <- .90       # p(pos | breast cancer ) 
spec <- (1 - .09) # 1 - p(fa) = 1 - (pos | no breast cancer)
source <- "Gigerenzer (2013), p. 213--221"

## 4. Down syndrome  [Source: Gigerenzer (2013), p. 222--226]:
name <- "Down syndrome"
N <- 1000         # women (40yrs, pregnancy)
prev <- 10/1000   # p(Down syndrome)
sens <- .90       # p(pos | Down syndrome ) 
spec <- (1 - .05) # 1 - p(fa) = 1 - (pos | no Down syndrome)
source <- "Gigerenzer (2013), p. 222--226"

Data Structures

  1. Define some vectors of length N based on the (current) main variables:
## (0) Get current parameters:
cur.env <- e1

name <- cur.env$name
N <- cur.env$N
prev <- cur.env$prev
sens <- cur.env$sens
spec <- cur.env$spec 
source <- cur.env$source
  
## (1) Determine the truth:
n.true <- round((prev * N), 0)
n.false <- (N - n.true)

truth <- c(rep(TRUE, n.true), rep(FALSE, n.false))
# truth
sum(truth)
#> [1] 15

## (2) Determine decisions:
n.hi <- round((sens * n.true), 0)  # hits
# n.hi 
n.cr <- round((spec * n.false), 0) # correct rejections
# n.cr
n.mi <- (n.true - n.hi)            # misses
# n.mi
n.fa <- (n.false - n.cr)           # false alarms
# n.fa

decision <- c(rep(TRUE, n.hi), rep(FALSE, n.mi), rep(TRUE, n.fa), rep(FALSE, n.cr))
# decision
# sum(decision)

## (3) Combine truth and decisions:
both.true <-  truth & decision 
both.false <-  !truth & !decision
correct.dec <- both.true | both.false 
length(correct.dec)
#> [1] 100
sum(correct.dec)/N
#> [1] 0.77

## (4) Checks:
N == (n.hi + n.cr + n.mi + n.fa)
#> [1] TRUE
length(truth) == length(decision)
#> [1] TRUE
sum(truth) == n.hi + n.mi 
#> [1] TRUE
sum(decision) == n.hi + n.fa 
#> [1] TRUE
sum(both.true) == n.hi 
#> [1] TRUE
sum(both.false) == n.cr
#> [1] TRUE
sum(correct.dec) == n.hi + n.cr
#> [1] TRUE
  1. Populate the (total) population:

Goal: Define a common (global) data structure that is used and updated by all representations.

## (1) Initialize the population of individuals:

## (a) Population as a vector of lists (each of which is an individual):
i <- list(tru = NA, # true state of the individual (Boolean) 
          dec = NA, # decision on the individual (Boolean)
          sdt = ""  # category in SDT terms ("hi", "mi", "fa", "cr") 
          )
population <- rep(i, N)

## Populate the population with the values from above:
population$tru <- truth
population$dec <- decision

population$sdt[population$tru & population$dec]   <- "hi"
population$sdt[population$tru & !population$dec]  <- "mi"
population$sdt[!population$tru & population$dec]  <- "fa"
population$sdt[!population$tru & !population$dec] <- "cr"

## (b) Population as a data frame:
population <- data.frame(tru = truth,
                         dec = decision,
                         sdt = NA)
names(population) <- c("truth", "decision", "sdt")

population$sdt[population$tru & population$dec]   <- "hi"
population$sdt[population$tru & !population$dec]  <- "mi"
population$sdt[!population$tru & population$dec]  <- "fa"
population$sdt[!population$tru & !population$dec] <- "cr"

# head(population)
# dim(population)

## (2) Make sdt an ordered factor:
population$sdt <- factor(population$sdt, 
                         levels = c("hi", "mi", "fa", "cr"),
                         # labels = c("hit", "miss", "false alarm", "correct rejection"), # explicit labels
                         labels = c("hi", "mi", "fa", "cr"), # implicit labels
                         ordered = TRUE)
# is.factor(population$sdt)
# levels(population$sdt)

## Checks:
# population$sdt
table(population$sdt)
#> 
#> hi mi fa cr 
#> 13  2 21 64
(sum(population$sdt == "hi") + sum(population$sdt == "cr"))/N # => accuracy
#> [1] 0.77

Note that defining population as a data frame allows immediate access to its variables (columns), cases (rows), and cells. Additionally, a rectangular population can be easily displayed, ex- or imported, and sampled.

1. 2x2 confusion table

## Compute natural frequencies:

## (1a) Generate from basic parameters (see above):
## 1st row:
# n.true <- round((prev * N), 0)
# n.false <- (N - n.true)
## 2nd row:
# n.hi <- round((sens * n.true), 0)  # hits
# n.cr <- round((spec * n.false), 0) # correct rejections
# n.mi <- (n.true - n.hi)            # misses
# n.fa <- (n.false - n.cr)           # false alarms

## (1b) get from current population:
n.true <- sum(population$tru == TRUE)
n.false <- sum(population$tru == FALSE)

dec.pos <- sum(population$dec == TRUE)
dec.neg <- sum(population$dec == FALSE)

n.hi <- sum(population$sdt == "hi")
n.mi <- sum(population$sdt == "mi")
n.fa <- sum(population$sdt == "fa")
n.cr <- sum(population$sdt == "cr")

# Checks:
N == n.true + n.false
#> [1] TRUE
N == dec.pos + dec.neg
#> [1] TRUE
n.true  == n.hi + n.mi
#> [1] TRUE
n.false == n.fa + n.cr
#> [1] TRUE
dec.pos == n.hi + n.fa
#> [1] TRUE
dec.neg == n.mi + n.cr
#> [1] TRUE

# (2) Define some derived metrics:
acc <- (n.hi + n.cr)/N 
w.sens <- .50
bacc <- (w.sens * n.hi/(n.hi + n.mi)) + ((1 - w.sens) * n.cr/(n.cr + n.fa))
  
ppv <- n.hi / dec.pos # ppv = p(true positive | positive decision)
npv <- n.cr / dec.neg # npv = p(true negative | negative decision)

Showing 2 x 2 confusion table

Decision: true false Sums:
positive hi=21 fa=23 44
negative mi=4 cr=52 56
Sums: 25 75 N = 100

Derived metrics:

  • Accuracy: acc = 73%, bacc = 76.67%,

  • Test validities: PPV = 47.73%, NPV = 92.86%.

## Function to plot tree of natural frequencies 
## (using current environment variables (NOT population) as argument:
make.nftree <- function(env = cur.env) {
  
  ## Get current parameters:
  name <- cur.env$name
  N <- cur.env$N
  prev <- cur.env$prev
  sens <- cur.env$sens
  spec <- cur.env$spec
  source <- cur.env$source
  
  ## Tree with natural frequencies:
  ## Define names:
  names <- c(paste0("N = ", N), # Note: Using global variables (NOT population as argument)
             paste0(cond.true.lbl, ":\n",  n.true), 
             paste0(cond.false.lbl, ":\n", n.false), 
             paste0(sdt.hi.lbl, "s:\n",  n.hi), 
             paste0(sdt.mi.lbl, "es:\n", n.mi),
             paste0(sdt.fa.lbl, "s:\n",  n.fa), 
             paste0(sdt.cr.lbl, "s:\n",  n.cr)
  )
  
  ## Make matrix M:
  M <- matrix(nrow = 7, ncol = 8, byrow = TRUE, data = 0)
  
  M[2, 1] <- "prevalence" # paste0("prevalence = ", as.character(prev)) 
  M[3, 1] <- "(N - true)"
  M[4, 2] <- "sensitivity"
  M[5, 2] <- "(true - hi)"
  M[6, 3] <- "(false - cr)"
  M[7, 3] <- "specificity"
  
  ## Plot matrix M:
  pp <- plotmat(M,
                pos = c(1, 2, 4), 
                curve = 0.0,
                name = names,
                box.lwd = 1.5, # radx = 0.1, # rady = 0.05, 
                box.size = .10, 
                box.prop = 0.5,
                box.type = "square", # "circle",
                box.col = c(rep(col.sand.light, 3), sdt.colors[c("hi", "mi", "fa", "cr")]), # "lightyellow"
                shadow.col = "steelblue4", # "grey25" 
                shadow.size = 0.0, # .005 
                lwd = 1.2,
                cex.txt = .90,
                main = paste0(name, ":\nTree of natural frequencies\n", "(", source, ")")
  )
  
  return(pp)
  
}

## Check: 
nftree <- make.nftree(cur.env)

4. Graphical illustrations of PPV/NPV

# (1) Compute PPV and NPV as a function of prev, sens, and spec:
# (A) Using Bayes formula:
# as functions:
get.PPV <- function(prev, sens, spec) {
  PPV <- NA # initialize
  num <- (prev * sens)
  den1 <- num
  den2 <- (1 - prev) * (1 - spec)
  PPV <- num / (den1 + den2)
  return(PPV)
}

get.NPV <- function(prev, sens, spec) {
  NPV <- NA # initialize
  num.n <- (1 - prev) * spec
  den1.n <- num.n
  den2.n <- (prev) * (1 - sens)
  NPV <- num.n / (den1.n + den2.n)
  return(NPV)
}

# Compute current PPV and NPV values for prev.range:
PPV <- get.PPV(prev.range, sens, spec)
NPV <- get.NPV(prev.range, sens, spec)

# (B) Using natural frequencies:
# (a) choose some population: 
N <- 10^6 # (arbitrary, drops out later)
# (b) 1st row:
n.true <- (prev.range * N)
n.false <- (N - n.true)
# (c) 2nd row:
n.hi <- (sens * n.true)  # hits
n.mi <- (n.true - n.hi)  # misses
n.cr <- (spec * n.false) # correct rejections
n.fa <- (n.false - n.cr) # false alarms
# (d) derived metrics:
PPV.2 <- n.hi / (n.hi + n.fa) # ppv = p(true positive | positive decision)
NPV.2 <- n.cr / (n.cr + n.mi) # npv = p(true negative | negative decision)

# (C) Verify that both methods yield same results:
all.equal(PPV, PPV.2) 
#> [1] TRUE
all.equal(NPV, NPV.2) 
#> [1] TRUE

Plot PV curves using base R:

Generic functions for PPV and NPV:

## (1) Positive predictive value (PPV) from probabilities:
comp_PPV <- function(prev = num$prev, sens = num$sens, spec = num$spec) {

  PPV <- NA # initialize

  ## PPV = hits / positive decision = hits / (hits + false alarms):
  hi <- (prev * sens)
  fa <- (1 - prev) * (1 - spec)

  PPV <- hi / (hi + fa)

  return(PPV)
}

## (2) Negative predictive value (NPV) from probabilities:
comp_NPV <- function(prev = num$prev, sens = num$sens, spec = num$spec) {

  NPV <- NA # initialize

  ## NPV = cr / negative decision = cr / (cr + mi):
  cr <- (1 - prev) * spec
  mi <- prev * (1 - sens)

  NPV <- cr / (cr + mi)

  return(NPV)
}

## Utility function from 
## https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3932038/plot-a-legend-outside-of-the-plotting-area-in-base-graphics
add_legend <- function(...) {
  opar <- par(fig = c(0, 1, 0, 1), oma = c(0, 0, 0, 0), mar = c(0, 0, 0, 0), new = TRUE)
  on.exit(par(opar))
  plot(0, 0, type = 'n', bty = 'n', xaxt = 'n', yaxt = 'n')
  legend(...)
}

plot_PV <- function(prev, sens, spec, 
                    show.PVprev = TRUE, show.PVpoints = TRUE, log.scale = FALSE) {
  
  ## Compute current PVs:
  PPV <- comp_PPV(prev, sens, spec)
  NPV <- comp_NPV(prev, sens, spec)
  
  ## Text labels:
  prev.lbl <- paste0("prev = ", as_pc(prev), "%")
  PPV.lbl <- paste0("PPV = ", as_pc(PPV), "%")
  NPV.lbl <- paste0("NPV = ", as_pc(NPV), "%")
  sens.spec.lbl <- paste0("(sens = ", as_pc(sens), "%, spec = ", as_pc(spec), "%)")
  title.lbl <- paste0("PV plot of current scenario", "\n", sens.spec.lbl)
    
  ## Parameters:
  col.prev <- grey(.50, alpha = .99) # prevalence # WAS: col.green.2
  col.axes <- grey(.10, alpha = .99) # axes
  col.bord <- grey(.10, alpha = .50) # borders (e.g., of points)
  cex.lbl <- .8 # size of text labels
  h.shift <- .088
  v.shift <- .030
  low.PV  <- .200 # threshold value for judging PPV or NPV to be low
  v.raise <- .700 # vertical raise of y-prev when PPV or NPV < low.PV
  
  ## Plot area:
  plot(0, xlim = c(0, 1), ylim = c(0, 1), axes = FALSE, ylab = "Probability", xlab = "Prevalence", type = "n")
  
  ## Title: 
  title(title.lbl, adj = 0.0, line = 1.0)
  
  ## Axes: 
  axis(side = 1, at = seq(0, 1, by = .1), labels = seq(0, 1, by = .1), 
       pos = 0, tck = -.02, col.axis = col.axes, col.ticks = col.axes) # x at bottom
  axis(side = 1, at = seq(0, 1, by = .1), labels = FALSE,              
       pos = 1, tck = -.02, col.axis = col.axes, col.ticks = col.axes) # x at top
  axis(side = 2, at = seq(0, 1, by = .1), labels = seq(0, 1, by = .1), 
       pos = 0, tck = -.02, col.axis = col.axes, col.ticks = col.axes) # y at left
  axis(side = 4, at = seq(0, 1, by = .1), labels = seq(0, 1, by = .1), 
       pos = 1, tck = -.02, col.axis = col.axes, col.ticks = col.axes) # y at right
  
  ## Grid:
  grid(col = grey(.8, .8))
  
  ## Curves:
  ## PPV:
  curve(expr = comp_PPV(x, sens, spec), from = 0, to = 1, add = TRUE, lty = 1, lwd = 2, col = col.ppv)
  ## NPV:
  curve(expr = comp_NPV(x, sens, spec), from = 0, to = 1, add = TRUE,  lty = 1, lwd = 2, col = col.npv)
  
  ## Lines:
  if (show.PVprev){
    abline(v = prev, lty = 2, lwd = 1, col = col.prev) # prev as vline
  }
  # abline(h = PPV, lty = 3, lwd = 1, col = col.ppv) # PPV as hline
  # abline(h = NPV, lty = 3, lwd = 1, col = col.npv) # NPV as hline
  # segments(x0 = 0, y0 = PPV, x1 = prev, y1 = PPV, lty = 2, lwd = 1.5, col = col.ppv) # PPV to y-axes
  # segments(x0 = 0, y0 = NPV, x1 = prev, y1 = NPV, lty = 2, lwd = 1.5, col = col.npv) # NPV to y-axes
  
  ## Points:
  ## prev:
  if (show.PVprev){
    if ((NPV < low.PV) | (PPV < low.PV)) { # y at v.raise:
      points(x = prev, y = 0 + v.raise, pch = 21, cex = 2, lwd = 1.5, col = col.bord, bg = col.prev)
    } else { # y at bottom (y = 0): 
      points(x = prev, y = 0, pch = 21, cex = 2, lwd = 1.5, col = col.bord, bg = col.prev)
    }
  }
  
  if (show.PVpoints) {
    ## PPV: 
    points(x = prev, y = PPV, pch = 21, cex = 2, lwd = 1.5, col = col.bord, bg = col.ppv)
    ## NPV:
    points(x = prev, y = NPV, pch = 21, cex = 2, lwd = 1.5, col = col.bord, bg = col.npv)
  }
  
  ## Labels:
  ## prev label:
  if (show.PVprev){
    if ((NPV < low.PV) | (PPV < low.PV)) { # y at v.raise:
      if ((prev < .50) | !(prev > 1 - h.shift)) {
        text(x = prev + h.shift, y = 0 + v.raise, labels = prev.lbl, col = col.prev, cex = cex.lbl) # on right
      } else {
        text(x = prev - h.shift, y = 0 + v.raise, labels = prev.lbl, col = col.prev, cex = cex.lbl) # on left+
      }
    } else { # y at bottom (y = 0): 
      if ((prev < .50) | !(prev > 1 - h.shift)) {
        text(x = prev + h.shift, y = 0 + v.shift, labels = prev.lbl, col = col.prev, cex = cex.lbl) # on right
      } else {
        text(x = prev - h.shift, y = 0 + v.shift, labels = prev.lbl, col = col.prev, cex = cex.lbl) # on left+
      }
    }
  }
  
  if (show.PVpoints) {
    ## PPV label:
    if ((PPV < .75 & !(prev > 1 - h.shift)) | (prev < h.shift)) {
      text(x = prev + h.shift, y = PPV + .000, labels = PPV.lbl, col = col.ppv, cex = cex.lbl) # on right
    } else {
      text(x = prev - h.shift, y = PPV + v.shift, labels = PPV.lbl, col = col.ppv, cex = cex.lbl) # on left+
    }
    ## NPV label: 
    if (NPV > .75 | (prev < h.shift)) {
      text(x = prev + h.shift, y = NPV + v.shift, labels = NPV.lbl, col = col.npv, cex = cex.lbl) # on right+
    } else {
      text(x = prev - h.shift, y = NPV - v.shift, labels = NPV.lbl, col = col.npv, cex = cex.lbl) # on left-
    }
  }
  
  ## Legend:
  # legend("bottom", legend = c("PPV", "NPV"), 
  #       col = c(col.ppv, col.npv), lty = 1, lwd = 2, cex = 1, bty = "o", bg = "white")
  add_legend("topright", legend = c("PPV", "NPV"), lwd = 2, col = c(col.ppv, col.npv), 
             horiz = TRUE, bty = 'n')
  
}

3D graph

The following graphs illustrate how â for a given prevalence (prev) in some population â the metrics PPV and NPV vary as a function of the sensitivity (sens) and the specificity (spec) of the test:

## (1) Define parameters:
{
  ## Inputs:
  
  ## Compute PPV and NPV:
  cur.PPV <- get.PPV(prev, sens, spec)
  cur.NPV <- get.NPV(prev, sens, spec) 
  
  # prev <- .15 # prevalence (to be set in parameter)
  sens.range <- seq(0.0, 1.0, by = .05) # range of sensitivity values 
  spec.range <- seq(0.0, 1.0, by = .05) # range of specificity values 
  z.lim <- c(0, 1) # range of z-axis
  
  # Basic graph parameters:
  my.theta <- 40  # horizontal viewing angle (higher values: more rotation)
  my.phi <- 10    # vertical viewing angle (higher values: higher viewpoint)
  my.expand <- .9 # values < 1 shrink expansion in z-direction
  my.d <- 1.2     # values > 1 lessen perspective effect 
}

## (2) Compute PPV and NPV for an entire matrix of values:
pv.matrix <- function(prev, sens, spec, metric) {
  
  # initializing DF (as matrix to store and return results):
  n.rows <- length(sens)
  n.cols <- length(spec)
  matrix <- as.data.frame(matrix(NA, 
                                 nrow = n.rows, 
                                 ncol = n.cols)) 
  names(matrix) <- sens 
  
  # loop through all rows and columns of pc.matrix: 
  for (row in 1:n.rows) {
    for (col in 1:n.cols) {
      
      # Compute the needed model DV for the current cell value:
      cell.val <- NA 
      
      if (metric == "PPV") {cell.val <- get.PPV(prev, sens[row], spec[col])} # compute PPV
      if (metric == "NPV") {cell.val <- get.NPV(prev, sens[row], spec[col])} # compute NPV
      
      # Store results:
      matrix[row, col] <- cell.val 
      
    }
  }
  
  return(matrix)
  
}

## Use function to compute current values:
PPV.mat <- pv.matrix(prev, sens.range, spec.range, metric = "PPV")
NPV.mat <- pv.matrix(prev, sens.range, spec.range, metric = "NPV")

Some topics for future extensions:

Cell A bias and biased sampling of evidence

Contingency table

Assume the following:

  • 2 independent probabilities for features \(A\) and \(B\) that suggest a causal link (e.g., [\(A\) = nuclear power station and \(B\) = cancer] or [\(A\) = aluminum deodorant and \(B\) = cancer] etc.

  • \(A\) and \(B\) are statistically independent (not causally related)

A.cat <- c("alu", "no_alu") # A is binary
B.cat <- c("cancer", "healthy") # B is binary
pA <- .66
pB <- .10

# Simulation:
N <- 1000
A <- sample(x = A.cat, size = N, replace = TRUE, prob = c(pA, 1 - pA))
B <- sample(x = B.cat, size = N, replace = TRUE, prob = c(pB, 1 - pB))

# Contingency table:
BxA <- table(B, A)
BxA
#>          A
#> B         alu no_alu
#>   cancer   65     29
#>   healthy 614    292

# sums and percentages:
colSums(BxA)
#>    alu no_alu 
#>    679    321
rowSums(BxA)
#>  cancer healthy 
#>      94     906
as_pc(BxA/sum(BxA)) 
#>          A
#> B          alu no_alu
#>   cancer   6.5    2.9
#>   healthy 61.4   29.2

# 1st row percentages per column (pB):
as_pc(BxA[1,1]/sum(BxA[ , 1]))
#> [1] 9.57
as_pc(BxA[1,2]/sum(BxA[ , 2]))
#> [1] 9.03

# 1st col percentages per row (pA)
as_pc(BxA[1,1]/sum(BxA[1, ]))
#> [1] 69.15
as_pc(BxA[2,1]/sum(BxA[2, ]))
#> [1] 67.77

# Focus on row 1 suggests causal relationship A->B (which is simply due to pA).

Biased sampling

Now assume that we do not have access to the overall contingency table, but only instances of individual cases in memory, from which we sample (or to which we selectively attend).

  • Unbiased sampling would approximate the true contingency table.

  • However, focusing on particular dimensions (of \(A\) or \(B\)) would yield biased tables and estimates.

Conclusion

Important Insights

Materials for conclusions and possible quizzes:

  • The sensitivity and specificity of a diagnostic test are insufficient to determine its PPV and NPV.

  • Both PPV and NPV crucially depend on the specific prevalence of a particular person. Thus, always use an appropriate reference group to specify the risk of a particular person as accurately as possible.

  • PPV and NPV show opposite trends (as a function of prevalence): When one is high, the other one tends to be low (and vice versa).

    • with increasing prevalence: PPV increases.

    • with increasing prevalence: NPV decreases.

Recommendations for the General Population

  • A risk-literate person should be aware that any diagnostic test (or clinical judgment) has 4 possible outcomes: 2 possible correct and 2 possible incorrect judgments.

  • Whenever receiving a (positive or negative) test result, a good question is: What is the probability that this result is wrong?

    • Whenver receiving a positive (undesirable) test result: What is the PPV vs.Â p(false alarm) for me (or a random person from my reference group)?

    • Whenever receiving a negative (desirable) test result: What is the NPV vs.Â p(miss) for me (or a random person from my reference group)?

Recommendations for Risk Professionals (e.g., Medical Health Experts)

More challenging conclusions and demands:

  • All risk professionals should know how to determine and evaluate evidence for and against treatments (as a function of all 4 cells, rather than committing cell A bias).

  • All risk professionals should be able to define and distinguish between sensitivity and PPV (as opposite conditional probabilities), as well as specificity and NPV (sic).

  • All risk professionals should be able to use contingency tables, natural frequency trees, and icon arrays to solve Bayesian problems (of conditional probability).
